items.title: Just squeeze in -- when spaces are tight, nature loosens its laws
items.summary: It turns out that when they're in a hurry and space is limited, ions, like people, will find a way to cram in -- even if that means defying nature's norms. Researchers have now shown that the charged particles will actually forgo their 'opposites attract' behavior, called Coulombic ordering, when confined in the tiny pores of a nanomaterial.

alternate.title: Just squeeze in -- when spaces are tight, nature loosens its laws

items.title: Step towards better 'beyond lithium' batteries
items.summary: A step towards new 'beyond lithium' rechargeable batteries with superior performance has been made.

items.title: Myth Debunked that OCD Is Associated With Superior Intelligence
items.summary: Researchers conducted a meta-analysis of all the available literature on IQ in OCD samples versus non-psychiatric controls (98 studies), and found that contrary to the prevailing myth, OCD is not associated with superior IQ, but with normative IQ that is slightly lower compared to control samples. The authors suggested that the small reduction in IQ scores in OCD sufferers may be largely attributed to OCD-related slowness and not to intellectual ability.

alternate.title: Myth Debunked that OCD Is Associated With Superior Intelligence

items.title: Scientists show molecular basis for ants acting as 'bodyguards' for plants
items.summary: Though you might not think of ants as formidable bodyguards, some do an impressive job protecting plants from enemies. Examing the relationship between the Amazon rainforest plant Cordia nodosa in Peru and the ant species Allomerus octoarticulatus, scientists found the degree to which the ants express two genes significantly impacts the amount of protection they provide to their hosts.

alternate.title: Scientists show molecular basis for ants acting as 'bodyguards' for plants

items.title: Scalable process discovered to produce structural colors inspired by bird feathers
items.summary: Researchers made nano-sized balls of melanin aggregate into clusters called supraballs. Melanin appears black in individual nanoparticles. But altering spacing of the nanoparticles in the ball affects how the particles scatter light. A thin silica coating on the outside of melanin nanoparticles acts like a bumper, limiting how close the particles can pack together. Varying the diameter of the melanin core and the thickness of the silica shellÂ creates supraballs in a range of colors.

items.title: Physicists discover a tri-anion particle with colossal stability
items.summary: Chemists have created the most stable tri-anion particle currently known to science. A tri-anion particle is a combination of atoms that contains three more electrons than protons. This discovery is novel because previously known tri-anion particles were unstable due to their numerical imbalance.

alternate.title: Physicists discover a tri-anion particle with colossal stability

items.title: When radio galaxies collide, supermassive black holes form tightly bound pairs
items.summary: Supermassive black holes found in the centers of galaxies can form gravitationally bound pairs when galaxies merge, according to a new study.
